If you recently tried pairing Bun with a newer version of Mongoose (v8 or v9), your server probably died immediately on startup with this exact stack trace:
NotImplementedError: node:v8 isBuildingSnapshot is not yet implemented in Bun.
code: "ERR_NOT_IMPLEMENTED"
at <anonymous> (…/node_modules/bson/lib/bson.cjs:2610:30)Your code isn’t broken. The problem actually comes from a deep dependency collision involving Bun’s internal polyfills.
Why it happens
Mongoose relies on the official MongoDB Node.js driver, which uses a library called `bson` for data serialization. Starting in version 6.8.0, the `bson` package added a minor performance check that runs the second the module is loaded: it calls `v8.startupSnapshot.isBuildingSnapshot()`.
Bun tries to be a seamless drop-in replacement for Node.js by polyfilling core modules like `node:v8`. The catch? They haven’t finished building the `startupSnapshot` feature yet. Instead of gracefully returning `false`, Bun throws a hard `ERR_NOT_IMPLEMENTED` error.
Because of how module resolution works, the split second you import Mongoose, that BSON file gets evaluated, hits the unimplemented Bun polyfill, and brings down your entire application.
The trap: Inline patching
A lot of developers try to hack their way around this by mocking the function right at the top of their entry file:
// ❌ This doesn’t work in ES Modules!
import v8 from 'v8';
v8.startupSnapshot.isBuildingSnapshot = () => false;
import mongoose from 'mongoose'; // ← Still crashesThis fails because ES Modules hoist imports. The JavaScript engine parses your file, finds the `import mongoose` statement, and evaluates that entire dependency tree long before your inline `v8.startupSnapshot` patch ever executes. Mongoose still crashes because the patch was too late.
The actual fix: Bun’s ` — preload` flag
To beat the module loader, you have to run your patch globally before the application even boots. Bun has a native ` — preload` argument designed exactly for this.
First, create a dedicated patch file. We need to use `Object.defineProperty` here to safely bypass any internal getters Bun might have set up on that module.
// src/patch.ts
if (globalThis.process && globalThis.process.getBuiltinModule) {
try {
const v8 = globalThis.process.getBuiltinModule('v8');
if (v8) {
Object.defineProperty(v8, 'startupSnapshot', {
value: {
isBuildingSnapshot: () => false
},
configurable: true,
writable: true
});
}
} catch (e) {
// Ignore errors in older environments
}
}Next, tell Bun to load this file before doing anything else.
If you run your code via `package.json`, update your start script:
{
"scripts": {
"start": "bun - preload ./src/patch.ts dist/index.js"
}
}If you use `nodemon` for local development, update your config:
{
"exec": "bun - preload ./src/patch.ts src/index.ts"
}That’s it. Bun now evaluates `patch.ts` in complete isolation. When it finally moves on to your actual application code, the `v8` module is already safely mocked. Mongoose loads cleanly, and your server boots up without the crash.
